 SHAKE128 vs SHAKE256
  Both SHAKE128 and SHAKE256 are extendable-output functions (XOFs) built on the same Keccak-f[1600]
  permutation and the same sponge construction. They differ only in how the 1600-bit state is split
  between rate and capacity.

  Core Parameters
  Property              SHAKE128                SHAKE256
  Permutation           Keccak-f[1600]          Keccak-f[1600]
  Rate(r)               1344 bits(168 bytes)    1088 bits (136 bytes)
  Capacity(c)           256 bits                512 bits
  Security level        128                     256


 SHA-3 Padding: Domain Separation and Message Finalization
 SHA-3 uses a carefully designed padding scheme that serves two distinct but equally important purposes:
 domain separation and the final padding bit, which marks the end of the message.

 Domain Separator Byte
 The domain-separator byte prepositions the hash block and enforces alignment between the input and the
 intended construction. Its purpose is to ensure that same message, when processed under different hash-
 function paradigms built on the same permutation, cannot collide or be misinterpreted.

 The main purpose of domain-separator byte to identify which hash-function construction is being used on
 top of the Keccak permutation.

 - SHA-3 fixed-length hashes use 0x06
 - SHAKE extendable-output functions use 0x1F

 Although SHA-3 and SHAKE share the same Keccak-f[1600] permutation, they must operate in distinct
 cryptography domains. If we do a quick test an input msg "Hello World" and run against all SHA-3
 and SHAKE hash-functions then output block will be different.

 func TestHelloWorldHash(t *testing.T) {
 	msg := "Hello World"
 	for _, paradigm := range []string{"SHA3-224", "SHA3-256", "SHA3-384", "SHA3-512", "SHAKE128", "SHAKE256"} {
 		var s State
 		switch paradigm {
 		case "SHA3-224":
 			s = New224()
 		case "SHA3-256":
 			s = New256()
 		case "SHA3-384":
 			s = New384()
 		case "SHA3-512":
 			s = New512()
 		case "SHAKE128":
 			s = NewShake128()
 		case "SHAKE256":
 			s = NewShake256()
 		}
 		h := make([]byte, 64)
 		msgBytes := []byte(msg)
 		s.Write(msgBytes)
 		s.Read(h[:])
 		fmt.Println("Paradigm = ", paradigm, " - hashBlocks = ", h)
 	}
 }

